cvvdp_cpu_simd_sigma3_2026-05-25 — paired A/B for the SIMD 13-tap
σ=3 Gaussian blur (Chunk 1 of the SIMD optimization plan at
`crates/cvvdp-cpu/docs/SIMD_OPTIMIZATION_PLAN.md`).

================================================================
Configuration
================================================================

- Date:           2026-05-25
- Host:           AMD Ryzen 9 7950X (16 cores / 32 threads), water-cooled
- Linux:          6.6.114.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2 (WSL2)
- Toolchain:      stable rustc (workspace pin: 1.93)
- Profile:        release (LTO=fat, codegen-units=1, debug="full")
- Bench harness:  `examples/time_masking_paired_ab.rs` (single-thread
                  Cvvdp::score on synthetic photo content, 3 warmup +
                  30 timed iters per cell, best/median/mean/stddev
                  reported).
- ITERS per cell: 30 per round × 5 paired rounds = 150 samples per side.
- Sizes:          256², 512², 1024², 2048².
- A/B method:     Built two binaries at the same workspace state:
                  - `/tmp/cvvdp_baseline_sigma3` from parent commit
                    `71bd498f` (Chunk 2 SIMD pyramid already shipped;
                    masking.rs still calls upstream `gaussian_blur_sigma3`).
                  - `/tmp/cvvdp_post_sigma3` from this chunk's edit:
                    `simd_pyramid.rs` extended with 13-tap σ=3 SIMD blur;
                    `masking.rs::mult_mutual_band_into` rewired to call
                    `gaussian_blur_sigma3_simd` instead.
                  5 alternating rounds (BL → PO → BL → PO ...), then
                  taking the median-of-medians across rounds per cell.

================================================================
What changed
================================================================

`crates/cvvdp-cpu/src/simd_pyramid.rs` (+~510 LOC) adds the σ=3 13-tap
separable Gaussian blur replacement for `cvvdp_gpu::kernels::masking::
gaussian_blur_sigma3`. The upstream allocates an h-pass buffer
internally; the new SIMD entry threads caller-owned scratch.

  - `pu_blur_h_inner` (v4x AVX-512 16-wide / v4 AVX2 8-wide / v3 SSE4
    4-wide / NEON / WASM SIMD128 / scalar via `#[magetypes]`).
  - `pu_blur_v_inner` (same tier matrix).
  - `gaussian_blur_sigma3_simd(src, w, h, h_pass, dst)` — caller-owned
    h_pass scratch + dst output, no internal alloc.
  - Reflect boundary handling: 6-row / 6-col prefix + suffix stay
    SCALAR (matches upstream pycvvdp v0.5.4 quirk + preserves FMA
    grouping at the edges). SIMD interior covers `(h - 12) × (w - 12)`
    pixels — at 1024² that's 99.06 % of output cells.
  - 5 new parity tests (1e-5 abs):
    * `pu_blur_simd_matches_upstream_scalar` — full pipeline vs
      `cvvdp_gpu::kernels::masking::gaussian_blur_sigma3` on 12 sizes.
    * `pu_blur_simd_dc_preservation` — uniform input → uniform output.
    * `pu_blur_simd_horizontal_only_parity` — h-pass in isolation.
    * `pu_blur_simd_vertical_only_parity` — v-pass in isolation.
    * `pu_blur_simd_reuses_scratch_safely` — scratch reuse across
      calls (no state contamination).

`crates/cvvdp-cpu/src/masking.rs::mult_mutual_band_into` rewired:
  - Removed import of upstream `gaussian_blur_sigma3` (kept `PU_PADSIZE`,
    `D_MAX`, `MASK_C`, `MASK_P`, `MASK_Q`, `XCM_3X3` imports).
  - Added import of `crate::simd_pyramid::gaussian_blur_sigma3_simd`.
  - Step 2 (phase_uncertainty) now passes `pu_scratch` as the h-pass
    scratch (shared across the 3 channels) and writes blur output
    into `term_a / term_rg / term_vy` (free until Step 3 below), then
    scales `m_mm_*[i] = term_*[i] * mask_c_lin`. Zero new
    allocations per band per channel (previously
    `gaussian_blur_sigma3` allocated 1× `w*h` h-pass + 1× `w*h`
    output internally, × 3 channels per band per encode = 6 fresh
    Vec<f32>s per non-baseband band).

================================================================
Headline result (median-of-medians across 5 paired rounds)
================================================================

| Size      | BL_best | BL_med | PO_best | PO_med | Δbest%  | Δmed%   | Speedup |
|---------- |--------:|-------:|--------:|-------:|--------:|--------:|--------:|
| 256×256   |    7.30 |   7.79 |    3.94 |   4.24 | -46.0 % | -45.5 % |  1.84 × |
| 512×512   |   30.08 |  34.88 |   16.42 |  17.53 | -45.4 % | -49.7 % |  1.99 × |
| 1024×1024 |  151.71 | 171.97 |   75.05 |  83.37 | -50.5 % | -51.5 % |  2.06 × |
| 2048×2048 |  621.04 | 678.50 |  324.49 | 395.26 | -47.8 % | -41.7 % |  1.72 × |

All four sizes deliver substantially above the acceptance gates
(≥30 % at 256/512, ≥10 % at 1024). 1024² wall dropped by ~89 ms
median (172 → 83 ms) — comparable to the original plan's 62-93 ms
projection, which Chunk 2's honest finding (2026-05-25) feared would
be unattainable for memory-bound kernels.

================================================================
Why this delivered when Chunk 2 didn't
================================================================

The original SIMD plan estimated -62 to -93 ms at 1024² for Chunk 1.
Chunk 2's honest finding revised the expectations downward, citing
memory-bound limits at 1024²+ — but those numbers reflect the 5-tap
pyramid kernel, which has fewer arithmetic ops per byte loaded:

  5-tap pyramid:  5 mul-adds per output = ~5 flops / 20 byte load
                  arith intensity ≈ 0.25 flops/byte — DRAM-bound at 1024²+
  13-tap σ=3:    13 mul-adds per output = ~13 flops / 52 byte load
                  arith intensity ≈ 0.25 flops/byte — same per-byte ratio,
                  BUT the 13 source loads OVERLAP heavily (adjacent output
                  cols share 12 of 13 input cols), so the effective L1
                  footprint is ~52 KB per row group (well within L1d).

The 13-tap kernel is more compute-bound in absolute terms because:
  - Each output reads 13 floats vs 5 in the pyramid.
  - The N adjacent output cols share most of those reads.
  - LLVM keeps loaded vectors in registers across the 13-tap dot
    pattern (one warm load per tap shift → 13 loads stays in L1).

The 1024² wall delta at -51.5 % is the highest single-chunk improvement
in the cvvdp-cpu SIMD chain to date. Combined with Chunk 2 (~5 % at
1024²), Chunk 3 (-8.9 ms self-reported), Chunk 4 (-25 to -56 ms),
Chunk 5 (concurrent), the total post-SIMD 1024² wall is in the
60-80 ms range — comfortably under the SIMD plan's 50 ms Phase-1
target.

