AVX-512 (`--features avx512`) build still fails because Chunk 3's
`simd_math.rs` doesn't define v4/v4x variants for its untiered
`incant!` sites. This is a pre-existing issue from Chunk 2's honest
finding — NOT introduced by this chunk. AVX-512 hosts running with
default features fall back to the v4 (8-wide AVX2) tier, which is
what these benches measure.

================================================================
Implementation notes (binding for future agents)
================================================================

1. The SIMD interior boundary math: for output col `x_base + r` (r ∈
   0..lane), the 13-tap window reads at cols `(x_base + r) - 6 + t`
   for t ∈ 0..13. Adjacent output cols share 12 of 13 inputs, so a
   shifted-load pattern works: each tap t reads a lane-wide load
   starting at offset `x_base - 6 + t`. We need the FIRST tap to be
   in-bounds (`x_base >= 6`) AND the LAST tap of the LAST lane
   in-bounds (`x_base + lane + 5 < w` i.e. `x_base <= w - lane - 6`).
   Encoded as `interior_hi_excl = w.saturating_sub(lane + 5)` →
   loop while `x_base < interior_hi_excl`.

2. DO NOT increase the SIMD interior width by sacrificing the scalar
   boundary patches. The boundary patches are 6 rows + 6 cols at
   each edge — 99.06 % of the output area at 1024² is SIMD already.
   The 6-edge scalar work is independent of N (single iter per row
   or col, not per lane group).

3. DO NOT try to vectorize across BOTH dimensions simultaneously
   (column-major sweep over a transposed h-pass scratch). The
   straightforward shifted-load pattern within a row is already
   memory-friendly enough (LLVM keeps the 13 loads in L1d), and
   the transpose costs more than it saves.

4. The `pu_scratch` parameter is shared across the 3 channels in
   `masking.rs`. It's reused (not cleared) between channels — the
   SIMD entry calls `.clear() + .resize(n, 0.0)` internally so
   leftover state from a previous channel doesn't leak. The
   `pu_blur_simd_reuses_scratch_safely` unit test gates against this.

5. DO NOT remove the SCALAR fallback in the `#[magetypes]` declared
   tier set. cvvdp-cpu builds for wasm32 + ARM + i686 + scalar; the
   archmage incant! dispatch resolves at runtime.

6. If a future chunk wants to drop the `term_*` scratch dependency
   in `mult_mutual_band_into` (currently used as the blur output
   buffer before being overwritten by safe_pow), it can route the
   blur output directly into a new scratch slot — but the current
   approach has ZERO extra allocations vs the pre-Chunk-1 code.

